quran[7]{c,v,t,f}:
  7,31,"O Children of Adam, take your adornment at every mosque<sup>b </sup>, and eat and drink, but do not be extravagant; surely He does not love the extravagant{1}.",footnotes:1:[The Arabic word used is <i>masjid</i> which literally means ‘a place for prostration’.],footnotes:2:[The same Arabic word, <i>musrifeen,</i> is used for extremists.]
  7,32,"Say<sup>sg </sup>, “Who has forbidden Allah’s adornment which He has brought out for His servants and the good things among<i>(His) </i>provision?” Say, “They are for those who attained faith in the Earlier Life,exclusively{1}theirs on the Day of Resurrection.” Thus We detail the signs{2}for people who know.",footnotes:1:[Qira’at: Nafie’ read it as: “Say, ‘They are, for those who attained faith in the Earlier Life, exclusive on the Day of Resurrection.’”],footnotes:2:[The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’. It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.]
  7,33,"Say, “Indeed, My Lord has only forbidden obscenities—both manifest and secret—and sin and unjustified aggression, and that you associate with Allah that for which He has never bestowedany authority from on high{1} , and that you say about Allah what you know not.”",footnotes:1:Qira’at: Ibn Kathir, Abu Amr and Ya’qub read it as: “…for which He has never sent down any authority,”
  7,34,"And for every community there is an appointed term. So when their term has arrived, they cannot then delay by one hour nor can they advance."
  7,35,"O Children of Adam, whenever messengers from among you come to you, relating to you My signs<sup>e </sup>, then whoever becomes mindful<i>(of God) </i>and reforms—no fear{1}shall beupon them{2}nor shall they grieve.",footnotes:1:[The Arabic word used is <i>ayat</i> (singular <i>ayah</i>). <i>Ayah</i> means ‘sign’ or ‘proof’.],footnotes:2:[It is also used to denote the unit of text in the Qur’an, like ‘verse’ in poetry or ‘sentence’ in prose. Each such unit is considered a ‘sign’ from God.]
  7,36,"But those who disbelieved in Our signs and were too arrogant to accept them—those are the fellows of the Fire; therein they abide."
  7,37,"So who is more unjust than someone who has fabricated lies against Allah or has considered His signs to be a lie? Those<sup>b </sup>—their share of the decree will reach them. Until, when Our messengers have come to them to take their souls<i>(at death) </i>, they say, “Where is whatever you used to call upon apart from Allah?” They say, “They have strayed from us,” and they testify against themselves that they were deniers.",footnotes:1:A grammatical shift from singular to plural.
